         <h1>Balthus, Painter Whose Suggestive Figures Caused a Stir, Is Dead at 92 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Balthasar Klossowski , the painter internationally known as Balthus , died yesterday at his chalet in La Rossinière , Switzerland , near Gstaad . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 92 . <br><blue>3</blue>For the last 30 years of his long life , Balthus was among the most widely admired of European painters . <br><blue>4</blue>He had excelled as a portraitist ( notably of his painter colleagues André Derain and Joan Miró ) , as a painter of French landscapes in a tradition that went back to Nicolas Poussin , and as someone who had given a whole new spin to the notion of Parisian townscape . <br><blue>5</blue>When painting still lifes , he could stress the violence implicit in the presence of hammer and knife among the apparatus of everyday activities . <br><blue>6</blue>( It was not for nothing that in Paris he was a close friend of Antonin Artaud , proponent of the '' theater of cruelty . '' ) <br><blue>7</blue>He could depict a game of cards as a pastime with overtones of desperation . <br><blue>8</blue>Balthus was also admired as a stage designer for Shakespeare 's '' As You Like It , '' Shelley 's '' Cenci '' ( as adapted by Artaud ) , Albert Camus 's '' État de Siège '' and Mozart 's '' Così Fan Tutte . '' <br><blue>9</blue>In Emily Brontë 's '' Wuthering Heights , '' he found inspiration in 1934 and '35 for a long series of drawings , more than one of which rivaled the singular mood of Brontë herself in its portrayal of a frenetic wooing between young people . <br><blue>10</blue>But above all , Balthus was known for paintings of equivocal figure subjects , very young women in poses or situations that were regarded as enigmatic or suggestive or both . <br><blue>11</blue>Often these subjects were caught between dream and waking . <br><blue>12</blue>Sometimes there were more explicitly sexual elements , and these caused a minor scandal as early as 1934 , when he had his first one-man show at the Galerie Pierre in Paris . <br><blue>13</blue>Though never wholly discarded , the element of erotic provocation became more oblique in his later work . <br><blue>14</blue>( '' I used to want to shock , '' he once told a friend , '' but now it bores me . '' ) <br><blue>15</blue>In 1955 , he even agreed to tone down an erotic incident in '' The Street '' ( 1933 ) , a painting that had been bought by James Thrall Soby , one of his earliest American admirers , who later bequeathed it to the Museum of Modern Art in Manhattan . '' <br><blue>16</blue>I really do n't understand why people see the paintings of girls as Lolitas , '' he told the chief art critic of The New York Times , Michael Kimmelman , in 1996 . '' <br><blue>17</blue>My little model is absolutely untouchable to me . <br><blue>18</blue>Some American journalist said he found my work pornographic . <br><blue>19</blue>What does he mean ? <br><blue>20</blue>Everything now is pornographic . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>Switzerland</m_str> (1_20) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>Gstaad</m_str> (1_23) 	<br><blue>3(3)</blue>: <m_str>Some American journalist</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_5) 	<br><blue>4(6)</blue>: <m_str>I</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>My</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>me</m_str> (14_22) 	<m_str>me</m_str> (17_8) 	<m_str>my</m_str> (18_7) 	<br><blue>5(1)</blue>: <m_str>the Galerie Pierre</m_str> (12_28) 	<br><blue>6(2)</blue>: <m_str>It</m_str> (6_2) 	<m_str>the violence implicit in the presence of hammer and knife</m_str> (5_9) 	<br><blue>7(1)</blue>: <m_str>1996</m_str> (16_33) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>my work</m_str> (18_7) 	<m_str>his later work</m_str> (13_15) 	<br><blue>9(12)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (1_14) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_7) 	<m_str>Balthus</m_str> (3_11) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (5_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_10) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str>Balthus</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (9_10) 	<m_str>Balthus</m_str> (10_5) 	<